CHAPTER 9: THE TEST
MAT
Wednesday evening. Mat's apartment.
Two suitcases by the door. Rosa's and Isa's. Packed in a hurry.
Rosa's in the kitchen, confused. Worried. "Mateo, I don't understand. Why do we need to leave?"
"Just for a week, Ma. Maybe two." Mat's loading the last bag into his Honda. "Miguel said he'd love to have you. Riverside's nice. Quieter than here."
"But my job—"
"I called your supervisor. Told them you had a family emergency. They understand."
Rosa studies her son's face. She's not stupid. Knows something's wrong. "Mateo. What's happening?"
Mat can't tell her the truth. Can't explain that professional mercenaries might be watching their building. That Vincent Harlan's people could come looking for him. That if they do, everyone Mat loves is in danger.
"It's just safer, Ma. Please. Trust me."
Isa appears in the doorway. One bag over her shoulder. She's been quiet all day. Hasn't fought Mat on this. That scares him more than if she'd argued.
"Isa?" Rosa looks at her daughter. "You know what this is about?"
Isa looks at Mat. Then at Rosa. "No, Ma. But if Mat says we need to go, we need to go."
Rosa's eyes water slightly. Not crying. Just... tired. "My boys. Always protecting me. Never telling me anything."
Mat hugs her. "I'm sorry, Ma. I'll explain everything soon. I promise."
"You better." She pulls back. Touches his face. "And you be careful, mijo. (Son.) Whatever this is."
"I will."
They load into the Honda. Mat drives. Rosa in passenger seat. Isa in back.
The drive to Riverside is ninety minutes. Quiet. Radio playing low. Rosa dozes off halfway there.
Isa leans forward from the back seat. Whispers so Rosa doesn't wake.
"Are we ever coming back?"
Mat glances at her in the rearview mirror. "Yeah. Two weeks max."
"You promise?"
"I promise."
"And you? You'll be okay?"
Mat doesn't answer right away. Can't lie to her. But can't tell her the truth either.
"I'll be okay," he says finally.
Isa leans back. Doesn't believe him. But doesn't push.
They arrive at Miguel's house. Small. Clean. Riverside suburbs. Safe.
Miguel's at the door. Mid-thirties. Good guy. Works construction. Has a wife and two kids. Normal life.
"Tía Rosa!" (Aunt Rosa!) He hugs her. "Isa! Look at you, all grown up."
They go inside. Miguel's wife makes coffee. The kids are excited—visitors!
Mat stays for twenty minutes. Long enough to be polite. Not long enough to get comfortable.
He walks Isa outside while Rosa settles in.
"Two weeks," Mat says.
"Two weeks," Isa repeats. Then: "Mat. If something happens to you—"
"It won't."
"But if it does—"
"Isa." Mat takes her hands. "If something happens to me, you take care of Ma. You finish school. You become a nurse like you want. You live. You understand?"
Tears in her eyes now. "I don't want to."
"I know. But promise me anyway."
"I promise."
Mat hugs her. Holds her tight. His little sister. Nineteen years old. Too young to be thinking about funerals.
"I love you, Isa."
"Love you too, hermano." (Brother.)
Mat pulls away. Gets in his car. Doesn't look back.
If he looks back, he won't leave.
And he has to leave.
Because Friday night, Mat's either walking out of that restaurant a free man or he's dying trying.
Either way, Rosa and Isa are safe.
That's all that matters.

COLE
Wednesday night. Cole's apartment.
He hasn't been home in days. Too risky. Been staying at the safehouse.
But tonight he needs clothes. Needs to look professional for tomorrow's meeting with Vincent.
Cole stands in his closet. Staring at suits. Which one do you wear to convince your boss you're not betraying him?
His phone rings. Ray.
"Yeah?"
"You ready for tomorrow?" Ray's voice is rough. Strained.
"No. You?"
"I'm not the one walking into Vincent's office."
"Fair point." Cole pulls out a charcoal suit. Conservative. Professional. "You holding up?"
Silence. Then: "Seven days sober. Hands won't stop shaking. Can't sleep. Can't think straight. But yeah, I'm holding up."
"Ray—"
"I'm fine. Just... be careful tomorrow. Vincent's smart. He'll test you."
"I know."
"And Cole? If he knows—if he's sure—don't try to talk your way out. Just run."
"I'm not running."
"Then you're an idiot."
"Yeah. I know." Cole sets the suit on his bed. "Get some sleep, Ray."
"Haven't slept in three days. Not gonna start now."
Ray hangs up.
Cole sits on his bed. Stares at the suit.
Tomorrow. Two PM. Vincent's office.
Cole's rehearsed his story a dozen times. The missing money? Divorce settlement. Sarah took everything, needed cash fast, borrowed against future payments, planned to pay it back.
Plausible. Believable.
But Vincent's not stupid.
If he already knows the truth, no story will save Cole.
Cole lies back on his bed. Fully clothed. Stares at the ceiling.
Tries to sleep.
Can't.
Twelve hours until the meeting.
Twenty-four hours until the heist.
If Cole survives tomorrow, Friday's his last chance to burn Vincent's empire.
If he doesn't survive tomorrow...
Well.
Ray and Mat will have to finish it without him.

RAY
Wednesday night. Ray's apartment.
Three AM. Ray's still awake. Sitting at his table. Bottle in front of him.
Seven days sober.
One hundred sixty-eight hours.
The bottle's been open for five days now. Cap off. Sitting there. Tempting him. Testing him.
Ray stares at it.
His hands shake so badly he can barely hold a cigarette. His body's screaming. Withdrawal hitting hard. Sweating. Nauseous. Can't sleep. Can't eat.
Every cell in his body wants that drink.
Just one.
Just to stop the shaking.
Just to quiet the noise in his head.
Ray picks up the bottle.
Raises it.
Stops.
Ricardo Navarro's face in his mind. Mat's face at Griffith Park. The gun pointed at Ray's chest.
You watched them kill my father.
Three more faces. The men Vincent killed. The bodies on the news.
All because Ray hit Delgado's storage unit.
All because Ray's trying to do one good thing.
And the world keeps burning.
Ray sets the bottle down.
Doesn't screw the cap on.
Just... sets it down.
He pulls out his phone. Texts Mat: You get them out safe?
Mat responds immediately: Yeah. They're in Riverside. Safe.
Ray: Good.
Mat: You good?
Ray stares at the question. At the bottle. At his shaking hands.
Types: No. But I'm still here.
Mat: That's enough.
Ray sets the phone down.
Seven days sober.
And every day is harder than the last.
But he hasn't drunk yet.
Not yet.

CISCO
Wednesday night. Cisco's spot.
Flaco walks in. "Ese, I got something."
Cisco looks up from his desk. "Talk."
"Mat's family. His mom and sister. They left tonight. Mat drove them somewhere. I had someone follow."
"Where?"
"Riverside. Cousin's house."
Cisco leans back. Processes this.
Mat's moving his family. Getting them out of LA. Out of the neighborhood.
That's not the move of someone planning a small job.
That's the move of someone expecting war.
"Anything else?"
"Yeah." Flaco pulls out his phone. Shows Cisco a photo. Grainy. Taken from a distance. Mat talking to two other guys outside a storage unit in El Segundo. "These the guys he's working with."
Cisco studies the photo. Can't see faces clearly. But one's older—forties, maybe. The other's younger—late thirties. Both white. Professional-looking.
Not street. Not gang.
Something else.
"You get names?"
"Working on it. But ese, whatever Mat's into? It's big. And it's soon."
Cisco nods. "Keep watching. I want to know the second something happens."
Flaco leaves.
Cisco stares at the photo.
Mat's moving his family.
Which means Mat's expecting retaliation.
Which means Mat's about to do something that'll bring heat.
Vincent Harlan heat.
Cisco lights a cigarette. Thinks.
He gave Mat two weeks. It's been four days.
Ten days left.
But Cisco's running out of patience.
And if Mat brings Vincent's war to 38th Street?
Brotherhood or not, Cisco will do what he has to do.

COLE
Thursday. 1:45 PM.
Cole stands outside Vincent's building. Downtown LA. Glass tower. Twenty stories. Vincent's office is on the top floor.
Cole's wearing the charcoal suit. Looks professional. Confident.
Inside, he's terrified.
He checks his phone. Text from Ray: Good luck. Don't die.
Text from Mat: If you don't come back, we'll finish it.
Cole doesn't respond. Just pockets his phone.
Walks inside.
The lobby is marble and chrome. Security desk. Two guards. Professional.
"Cole Brennan. Here to see Mr. Harlan."
The guard checks his computer. "Twentieth floor. He's expecting you."
Cole takes the elevator. Watches the numbers climb. Thinks about running. Thinks about jumping out when the doors open and just... not going.
But that's suicide too.
The doors open. Twentieth floor.
Vincent's office suite. Glass walls. Expensive art. A receptionist who looks like she's never smiled in her life.
"Mr. Brennan. Mr. Harlan will see you now."
She gestures to the door. Cole walks through.
Vincent's office is massive. Floor-to-ceiling windows overlooking LA. Desk made of dark wood. Everything expensive. Everything controlled.
Vincent sits behind his desk. Mid-fifties. Average height. Forgettable face. The kind of man you'd pass on the street and never remember.
That's his power.
Two other men in the room. Standing by the walls. Security. Armed. Professional.
"Cole." Vincent gestures to the chair across from him. "Sit."
Cole sits.
Vincent studies him. Silent. Letting the tension build.
Finally: "Six years, Cole. You've been working for me for six years."
"Yes, sir."
"And in those six years, you've been impeccable. Clean work. No mistakes. No complaints."
"I appreciate that."
"Which is why I was surprised." Vincent opens a folder on his desk. "When I found discrepancies in your accounts."
Cole's heart pounds. Keeps his face neutral. "Discrepancies?"
"Forty-seven thousand dollars. Spread across multiple transactions over the last three weeks." Vincent looks up. "Where's the money, Cole?"
Cole takes a breath. Here it is. The test.
"Divorce settlement," Cole says. Voice steady. "Sarah took everything when she left. The house. The savings. Everything. I needed cash fast to cover expenses. I borrowed against future payments. Planned to pay it back within the month."
"Forty-seven thousand dollars."
"Custody lawyers aren't cheap."
Vincent leans back. Studies Cole. Silent.
Cole holds his gaze. Doesn't look away. Doesn't flinch.
If Vincent knows the truth, Cole's dead.
If Vincent's testing, looking weak confirms guilt.
So Cole holds his ground.
"Your wife left you," Vincent says finally.
"Yes."
"Took the children."
"Yes."
"Why?"
Cole's jaw tightens. "She thought I was having an affair. Couldn't explain where I was going, who I was meeting. The lies piled up. She left."
Vincent nods slowly. "And the lawyers?"
"I'm fighting for custody. Or I was. Before I realized I'd already lost."
Silence.
Vincent closes the folder.
"I believe you," he says.
Cole doesn't react. Doesn't breathe.
"But." Vincent's voice hardens. "I don't tolerate theft. Even with good reasons. You took from me without asking. That's disrespect."
"I understand."
"Do you?" Vincent stands. Walks to the window. Back to Cole. "Because six years ago, I gave you a choice. Work for me, or watch your family suffer. You chose work. And I've been generous. I've paid you well. Protected you. And this is how you repay me?"
"Sir—"
"Quiet." Vincent doesn't turn. "I'm talking."
Cole shuts up.
"You took forty-seven thousand dollars," Vincent continues. "You'll pay it back. With interest. Fifteen percent. By the end of the month."
Cole does the math. Fifty-four thousand. Impossible.
But he nods. "Understood."
"Good." Vincent turns now. Walks back to his desk. "And Cole? If I ever find you stealing from me again—for any reason—I won't be this understanding. Clear?"
"Yes, sir."
"Then we're done. You can go."
Cole stands. Walks to the door.
Vincent's voice stops him.
"Cole."
Cole turns.
Vincent's sitting at his desk. Expressionless. "Be careful. Los Angeles is dangerous these days. People disappearing. Bodies dropping. It would be unfortunate if something happened to you."
The threat is clear.
"I'll be careful," Cole says.
He walks out.
Takes the elevator down.
Gets to the lobby.
Keeps walking.
Gets to his car two blocks away.
Gets inside.
Locks the doors.
Sits there.
Breathing.
Alive.
Vincent bought the story.
Or Vincent's playing with him. Letting him think he's safe. Watching to see what Cole does next.
Either way, Cole's alive.
For now.
He pulls out his phone. Texts Ray and Mat: I'm out. He bought it. We're still on for tomorrow.
Ray: Thank Christ.
Mat: You sure he bought it?
Cole: No. But I'm alive. That's enough.
Cole starts the car.
Drives back to the safehouse.
Twenty-four hours until the heist.
Vincent suspects something. Maybe doesn't know what. But suspects.
Which means tomorrow night, La Mer will be crawling with security.
But they're doing it anyway.
Because running means death.
And fighting means a chance.
Even if it's a small one.

COLE
Thursday night. Safehouse.
Ray and Mat are already there when Cole arrives.
"How'd it go?" Ray asks immediately.
Cole sits. Lights a cigarette. "He knows something's wrong. But he bought the divorce story. Or he's pretending to buy it."
"What's the difference?" Mat asks.
"The difference is whether he's testing me or hunting me."
"And which is it?"
"Don't know yet." Cole exhales smoke. "But he threatened me. Said it would be 'unfortunate' if something happened to me. Said LA's dangerous these days."
"That's not subtle," Ray says.
"Vincent's not subtle when he wants you scared."
Silence.
Mat speaks first. "So tomorrow. We're really doing this."
"Yeah."
"Vincent knows something's up. Sterling Security's watching us. Cisco's investigating me. The FBI might be circling. And we're walking into Vincent's restaurant to rob a senator in front of a hundred people."
"Yeah."
"We're insane."
"Yeah."
Ray almost laughs. "At least we're all on the same page."
Cole pulls out the La Mer floor plans. Spreads them on the table.
"Last chance to back out," he says. Looking at both of them. "Once we walk in tomorrow, there's no turning back."
Mat looks at Ray. Ray looks at Mat. Both look at Cole.
"I'm in," Mat says.
"I'm in," Ray says.
"Good." Cole taps the floor plan. "Then let's make sure we don't die."
They spend the next three hours planning.
Every detail. Every contingency. Every escape route.
By midnight, they're as ready as they'll ever be.
Ray leaves first. Heading home to not sleep and not drink.
Mat second. Going back to his empty apartment. Rosa and Isa safe in Riverside.
Cole stays at the safehouse.
Stares at the wall.
La Mer floor plan. Senator's photo. Vincent's network.
Tomorrow night, everything changes.
They succeed, they've proven Vincent's not untouchable.
They fail, they die.
Simple as that.
Cole crushes out his cigarette.
Gets four hours of sleep.
Dreams of fire.
